WEBVTT

00:00:00.400 --> 00:00:06.320
Magic. Okay. So, we've heard three great talks, and all week we've heard great talks about people

00:00:06.320 --> 00:00:12.560
failing their way into success, right? And so, I want to talk about failure itself, not just

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:20.879
about how we fail to success. So, in my now almost 20-year career, I have failed a lot more than I

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:26.320
have succeeded. Like, a lot more than I have succeeded. And this happens for all of us when

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:31.840
we're tackling these really interesting or new or complex or stubborn problems, right?

00:00:32.799 --> 00:00:38.480
And I've learned, as I've moved from the more hands-on individual contributor role into work

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:44.320
leading on data governance in some particularly messy situations, that I've had to think about

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:51.759
not just the failures, but how we fail in these situations. And as I've worked through this,

00:00:51.840 --> 00:00:58.240
I've identified kind of core tenets of failure. And we'll go through those really quickly. I think,

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:04.320
first, it's safe to say failure is inevitable, right? And I don't mean this fatalistically or

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:10.080
pessimistically. I mean, like, cool. Failure is inevitable. Run with it, right? We're not building

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:16.000
easy things. We're not tackling easy problems. We're taking big swings. And so, failures are

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:22.000
going to happen. And the second principle is that failure is helpful. Failure is how we learn.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.639
The best discoveries are born out of failing, right? The reason we have sticky notes is because

00:01:26.639 --> 00:01:31.599
someone failed miserably at making a permanent glue. The reason we have artificial sweeteners

00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:37.519
is because someone failed so badly at making anti-ulcer medications and they didn't wash

00:01:37.519 --> 00:01:41.760
their hands before having lunch, right? Big failures. Cool things that came out of it.

00:01:42.239 --> 00:01:48.239
And I'm going to add a third one here. And that is that failure is a bias. And what do I mean by

00:01:48.239 --> 00:01:54.559
that? So, failure is the way failure is a bias is the way that you see failure is shaped by your

00:01:54.559 --> 00:02:03.519
experience, your role, your tools, your teams, and your culture. So, it's by nature it is distorting,

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:08.479
not just framing. So, I'm going to do an example on this of a big public failure,

00:02:08.479 --> 00:02:13.679
and that will be the healthcare.gov website. Some of you may remember it. For those that

00:02:13.679 --> 00:02:17.520
either don't remember it or were in public health and have blacked it out of your memories,

00:02:18.800 --> 00:02:23.919
the healthcare.gov was a federal insurance marketplace launched in 2013. And its goal,

00:02:23.919 --> 00:02:29.440
its main aim, was to be a one-stop shop for Americans looking to compare, review,

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:35.119
and purchase individual health insurance under the Affordable Care Act. Instead, the rollout was

00:02:35.119 --> 00:02:41.759
what could only be described as catastrophic. To give you an idea, on day one, 4.7 million unique

00:02:41.759 --> 00:02:48.000
users logged on. Only 12 people were able to click the link that said I want to start an application.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:56.720
12 out of 4.7 million. So, if you look into the ad nauseum levels of review of why this happened,

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:01.759
you start to see that each person involved or each person not involved but looking at this

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:07.279
had a different perspective and a different frame and a different blame. So, you know,

00:03:07.279 --> 00:03:12.320
the engineers are going to see failures in trying to tackle these large, complex, technically

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:18.000
difficult systems to build this site, and the project managers are seeing missed deadlines

00:03:18.000 --> 00:03:24.000
that are resulting from really compressed timelines and a lot of uncertainty. The GAO,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.279
or the finance departments, are seeing blown budgets, the results of high-risk contracts.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:34.559
You'll see these, you know, the senior leaders are seeing failures of communication and

00:03:34.559 --> 00:03:41.199
coordination resulting from the lack of a central leadership and not-coordinated senior leaders,

00:03:41.199 --> 00:03:48.479
and users felt frustrated, let down, annoyed, or outright scammed, right? So, this is the same failure

00:03:48.479 --> 00:03:53.440
but with completely different lenses. So, not every failure is going to come with wall-to-wall

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:58.320
press coverage and a dozen congressional hearings and get written into textbooks for us all to study

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:06.320
later. Most failures just fade away. So, we have to think about which failures become the stories

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:12.000
that we tell, and how do those stories shape what failure means to us and to our community,

00:04:12.559 --> 00:04:18.720
and then what are the patterns of these stories help us find? So, to answer these questions,

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:23.040
you know, people have been trying to understand and categorize failure for as long as they've

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:29.839
been trying to avoid failure, and there are a lot of different approaches. So, some groups organized

00:04:29.839 --> 00:04:35.519
by mechanism. So, how did it fail? Was it technical? Was it a user error? Was it a decision failure?

00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:43.600
Or by an effect? So, was this systemic, local, contained, catastrophic? Or maybe what did we

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:49.119
learn from this failure? If you've ever heard of intelligent failures or black swan failures

00:04:49.119 --> 00:04:55.440
or complexity-induced failures, and these are all incredibly useful ways of mapping a failure

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:01.040
in any given arena, right, in any space, and I've used these and other models as I've mapped failures

00:05:01.040 --> 00:05:06.239
before, and some may be stickier for you in different places, and I've found one that works

00:05:06.239 --> 00:05:12.239
for me at kind of a 30,000-foot level to categorize all the failures, and that's what I'm calling a

00:05:12.239 --> 00:05:17.920
taxonomy of failure, and I've broken it down into kind of three flavors, as it were, three buckets. So,

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:24.239
structural, symbolic, and ambient failure. So, structural failure, what do I mean by that? I mean

00:05:24.239 --> 00:05:30.320
catastrophic brittleness that shows up only under stress. You may know the XKCD comic,

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:35.279
this one, where, you know, all of modern digital infrastructure is resting precariously

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:40.720
on a dependency for a project some random person in Nebraska has been thanklessly maintaining since

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:46.160
2003. So, you know, that's the idea here, but I'm going to give a case study that some of you in

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:53.519
this room might have been involved in, which was the 2022 Southwest Airline holiday meltdown, and

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:59.440
to explain why this was a specific type of structural failure, I first have to explain

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:06.000
how flagships and budget airlines wrapped. So, bear with me. I hope this is simple. So, flagships are

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.839
like United, Delta, or American, the big airlines, they operate what's called a hub and spoke model,

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:16.640
right? So, they centralize at their big hubs, O'Hare is a United one, Atlanta is a Delta hub,

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:21.760
and they have extra staff, extra planes there, so that they can be really guaranteed to get all

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:27.920
their flights on time. Budget airlines, like Southwest, JetBlue, Spirit, are operating what's

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:33.359
called a point-to-point method. So, you know, they decentralize their crews, and they assign them to

00:06:33.359 --> 00:06:40.480
like a tour, and this enables them to, A, not rent out massive amounts of space at the biggest

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:45.920
airlines, you know, O'Hare, it's expensive to rent space there, but also they can serve more

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:51.679
smaller market locations by getting more planes there. So, there are pros to this approach, as

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:57.920
well as cons. So, what happened in 2022 was primarily the Denver airport went down because of ice. So,

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:02.559
basically, the whole day, Denver is out of commission. There were a couple other small ones,

00:07:02.559 --> 00:07:07.760
but none of the major hubs in the United States went down. So, for the flagships, they're mostly

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:13.679
fine. They continued the routes to airports that were open, and as a weird kind of bonus, they had

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:18.799
some stranded staff at, you know, their hubs at O'Hare, an extra plane or two where they could get

00:07:18.799 --> 00:07:24.880
some more people moving. So, they did, you know, pretty fine. But on the point-to-point methods,

00:07:24.880 --> 00:07:30.880
one canceled flight propagates the delay through the network, because each leg is dependent on

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:37.279
aircraft and crew available from previous legs of the tour, right? And because this model

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:44.320
decentralizes staff and crew and materials, airports aren't they don't have standby

00:07:44.320 --> 00:07:49.839
available to go to those next points. So, this should have been recoverable. You notice that

00:07:49.839 --> 00:07:54.160
this point-to-point method, Spirit Airlines, JetBlue, they had no problems. They came back

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:59.760
online, you know, kind of slowly with everybody else, but Southwest melted down, just straight up

00:07:59.760 --> 00:08:06.720
melted down. And that's because Southwest was operating with a really outdated staff

00:08:06.720 --> 00:08:12.640
distribution system software. And that meant that they really just had no idea where their

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:18.399
pilots were, where their flight attendants were. Flight attendants were going to their app on their

00:08:18.399 --> 00:08:21.760
phone and trying to check, okay, I'm stuck in Cleveland, now what do you want me to do?

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:28.399
And the app wouldn't load. They'd call their help desk, and they would be on hold for over 24 hours

00:08:29.040 --> 00:08:33.599
waiting to figure out what city they were to go to. They would wake up in the morning and see,

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:38.080
oh, I'm assigned, it's 11 a.m., and I'm assigned to the 3 p.m. to Cleveland. They would go to the

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:43.119
airport, get there at 1, and be told at the airport, oh, that Cleveland flight got canceled yesterday.

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:51.599
Right? So, that breakdown resulted in about 70% of flights from Southwest being canceled over a

00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:57.440
week. Reminder, even the other budget airlines came back up pretty quickly about in line with

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:04.640
the flagships. So, they had about it ended up being about $800 million in losses in quarter

00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:11.280
four alone for Southwest. And then in 2023, when the DOT investigated and specified this was a

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:18.559
business failure, not weather, they had to pay out another $740 million in fines, reimbursements,

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:25.039
refunds, et cetera. So, that meltdown was catastrophic because of brittleness, right?

00:09:25.039 --> 00:09:30.799
But the brittleness was already there. It was just an accepted failure before. It was known. We

00:09:30.799 --> 00:09:36.400
knew this was broken, but it was acceptable. This is just the year before, 2021. April and October.

00:09:36.400 --> 00:09:41.840
Southwest was called out for having particularly high cancellation rates. And if you read into

00:09:41.840 --> 00:09:46.479
these, it's actually quite funny because you'll find notes at the bottom of these articles saying

00:09:46.479 --> 00:09:52.400
Southwest canceled 10%, but other airlines only had to cancel 2%. Very interesting. Even other

00:09:52.400 --> 00:10:00.239
budget airlines. So, their framing of accepted failure and tolerating this thing, this broken

00:10:00.239 --> 00:10:05.520
software system, led them to a situation where the system can bend, the system can bend, the system

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:10.719
can bend, and the system broke. So, that's structural failure. Brittleness that hides until

00:10:10.719 --> 00:10:15.919
the system collapses. But not every failure is going to bring your system down. Some are going

00:10:15.919 --> 00:10:20.559
to fail loudly in public view and the damage is reputational more than operational. And I call

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:25.840
that symbolic failure. Loud public and reputational damage. And for that, we're going to talk about

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:31.679
the metaverse. So, depending on your perspective, the metaverse is either a bold vision for the

00:10:31.679 --> 00:10:39.679
future of the Internet or the best tech joke of the last decade. So, Meta poured tens of billions

00:10:39.679 --> 00:10:44.239
of dollars into this project, and what they got out of it were headlines and endless social media

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:51.280
posts about legless avatars and boring experiences. It was parodied endlessly. The

00:10:51.280 --> 00:10:56.880
system didn't break. This is still a good product underneath it all. It just failed publicly.

00:10:58.479 --> 00:11:04.239
So, symbolic failure is not just about being laughed at. It's what that ridicule does. So,

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:09.760
in the metaverse, leaders assumed because they could envision this grand future, everyone else

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:16.159
would see it, too. And hey, our reputation is technically solid. We have widely adopted popular

00:11:16.159 --> 00:11:23.039
social media products, and that biased them into believing that that stability and that popularity

00:11:23.039 --> 00:11:27.039
meant they couldn't really fail with this new thing, even though it's bigger. It's a bigger,

00:11:27.039 --> 00:11:31.200
it's a different thing. As long as the system doesn't collapse, we're going to be a success.

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:36.880
Our vision can't fail. Unfortunately, the next time someone else tries something like this,

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:43.840
the next big swing in this area, they're going to have to fight the ghosts of metaverse's failure.

00:11:43.840 --> 00:11:50.159
We're all going to be biased against this idea because of what happened with metaverse this

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:57.039
specific time. So, that's the symbolic failure, right? It's not about crashing planes or, you

00:11:57.039 --> 00:12:02.159
know, servers breaking or what have you. It's losing that credibility, and once the credibility

00:12:02.159 --> 00:12:08.159
erodes, it's really hard to rebuild. So, that's the spectacle of failure, and not every failure

00:12:08.159 --> 00:12:14.719
is that way. Some failures are creepy, insidious, and invisible. They don't break all at once.

00:12:14.719 --> 00:12:21.280
They erode over time, until suddenly one day you just go, wait, what? This isn't right. That's an

00:12:21.840 --> 00:12:26.960
ambient failure. And for this, I want to talk about Google flu trends. And that launched in

00:12:27.039 --> 00:12:33.280
2008, and if you worked in public health at the time, it seemed like magic. They were able to get

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:40.320
predictions for outbreaks of the flu weeks before the CDC saw it coming with their traditional

00:12:40.320 --> 00:12:45.679
clinical surveillance models, and they did this by tracking search terms for things like flu

00:12:45.679 --> 00:12:52.880
symptoms or pharmacies near me or how do I treat a fever or ordering tissues, what have you. And,

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:56.719
you know, this was it looked like the future. If you were in public health at this time, you were

00:12:56.719 --> 00:13:01.679
like, oh, this is great. We're going to track the social movement of something before it shows up in

00:13:01.679 --> 00:13:07.200
our hospitals. This is great. It was a bold vision, and it was a sea change at the time.

00:13:08.159 --> 00:13:13.599
But unfortunately, what happened is that that started to drift. The system started to move

00:13:14.159 --> 00:13:18.880
to be less reliable and seem weird, and because it was so successful at the beginning, everyone was

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:25.200
like, well, it has to be true. What are we missing on the clinical side then? That became the pivot

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:32.400
of, like, this can't be wrong, so this has to be wrong. And so it was offset, like, up to 140%.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:37.599
It almost more than doubled the expected cases of a week compared to the CDC surveillance.

00:13:37.599 --> 00:13:43.280
And the reason for that was because the definitions underneath were changing. So it used those Google

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:48.559
search trends, right? But people, the media started to talk about the flu more. We had,

00:13:48.559 --> 00:13:52.239
you know, big conversations about other places, and people were looking up those articles,

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:58.960
right? People were, you know, the algorithms that Google used itself started changing.

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:05.280
And so it was no longer measuring people looking for care. It was measuring people paying attention

00:14:05.280 --> 00:14:10.880
and hyping up flu. And so no longer were we looking at what we thought we were.

00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:15.919
We didn't change anything as the Google flu trends team. Not we. I was not a member. But

00:14:15.919 --> 00:14:21.520
underneath, the definitions changed without us understanding. So there was no day when it went

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:28.400
bad. It just slowly got worse. No one continued using it. They all moved away from it, and then

00:14:28.400 --> 00:14:34.479
one day they just turned it off in 2015. And so this is what makes ambient failures insidious,

00:14:35.359 --> 00:14:41.119
is that they rot invisibly. They are hidden to you unless you're really paying attention,

00:14:41.119 --> 00:14:46.080
and by the time you notice, the damage is embedded in your system. You are already making bad

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:50.400
decisions on it. You are already misplacing your confidence. You have already lost opportunities

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:54.960
because it rotted from underneath. The bias here was that overconfidence in the first,

00:14:55.520 --> 00:15:01.440
you know, those first years when it looked so good, as it started to drift away, like I said,

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:05.840
it can't be the flu trends. It's got to be our clinical surveillance that is incorrect.

00:15:06.719 --> 00:15:12.479
And then we write it ourselves later, but few people thought to ask, as soon as that ship

00:15:12.479 --> 00:15:17.440
started turning, is the data still measuring what we think the data is measuring? Few people ask

00:15:17.440 --> 00:15:23.200
that. So that's what I call an ambient failure. It's not loud, it's not spectacular, but it is

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:29.760
corrosive, and sometimes this can be worse than a sudden collapse. Because it fools you into

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:36.000
thinking everything is okay, and you're making decisions on that okay, but it's not. So these

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:40.559
types of failure, my three types of failure, don't live in isolation. They are interconnected,

00:15:40.559 --> 00:15:46.080
and there is a trap, and when you overprotect against one, you are creating exposure to another.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:51.919
So Southwest, they optimized their efficiency, and they allowed for some forgivable failures,

00:15:51.919 --> 00:15:56.960
and then the system collapsed. Or meta, when they took great pride in their structural,

00:15:56.960 --> 00:16:00.559
you know, they were protecting against a structural failure, they took a big swing

00:16:00.559 --> 00:16:06.400
with this public promise, and they suffered a really bad failure in that symbolic world.

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:12.880
And then Google flu trends was the reverse, is that the system didn't snap overnight. It slowly

00:16:12.880 --> 00:16:19.280
drifted. Those proxies were incorrect. So in each case, bias played a role. The leaders never ignored

00:16:19.280 --> 00:16:25.039
the list. Or the risk. They were just picking the ones they thought were going to lead to the

00:16:25.039 --> 00:16:31.440
worst outcomes, given what they knew. And that left them exposed. So that brings us to today.

00:16:32.559 --> 00:16:37.599
We're entering this world with AI, making risk decisions for us, and it is already doing that.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:44.000
And they're not reflecting just our personal biases, but they are compounding our personal

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:49.760
biases, right? They're automating them, they're scaling them, and do we have any input into them?

00:16:50.559 --> 00:16:55.919
Do we know all of the places where AI is making those decisions for us? Do you know where you're

00:16:55.919 --> 00:17:01.599
AI? You keep talking that out to your LLM, you're querying your results, but you're querying your

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:06.160
results based on your history of failure and the things that you are worried about most.

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:13.280
So AI is going to start to break things in all three of my categories in new ways, and in ways

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:20.319
that we have not yet imagined. As is the history of failure. We have imagined failure in various

00:17:20.319 --> 00:17:25.599
different ways, all the way from moral failing to normal accidents to our high efficiency systems

00:17:25.599 --> 00:17:31.359
where nothing can fail, all the way to move fast and break things and into wherever we're going now.

00:17:32.640 --> 00:17:38.719
And it's really important to understand that the challenge isn't whether the failure is going to

00:17:38.719 --> 00:17:44.160
happen, it's whether we're going to recognize which failures we're inheriting, which ones we're

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:49.520
creating, and which ones we're ignoring or we don't see coming. So I don't want you to walk out of

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:53.439
here thinking that failure is something to fear. I think we heard a great keynote this morning that,

00:17:53.439 --> 00:17:59.280
like, don't be afraid of failure. Failure and running headlong into it is actually a good thing,

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:05.520
because that's how you learn. But paying attention to your own historical bias, your

00:18:05.599 --> 00:18:11.599
organizational bias, and your societal bias, it doesn't mean eliminating it, it means paying

00:18:11.599 --> 00:18:16.079
attention to it and getting better at learning from it. And so I'm going to leave you with a

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:21.119
Ben Franklin quote that I really like, is that perhaps the history of errors of mankind, all

00:18:21.119 --> 00:18:26.239
things considered, is more valuable and interesting than that of their discoveries. Truth is uniform

00:18:26.239 --> 00:18:32.160
and narrow, but error is endlessly diversified. And that's what makes it really cool. So thank you.

00:18:39.359 --> 00:18:45.920
Thank you so much. We have a couple of questions here. The first one, in the year 2000,

